text.tspan: US Law
Description
Process
International Emergency Economic
Powers Act (IEEPA) of 1977, Trade
with the Enemy Act of 1917
Used in times of war or national emergency, the President can have
power over all forms of international commerce, and the power to
freeze or seize foreign-owned assets
Currently used to impose tariffs on a wide range of trade partners, including the April 2/
August 1 tariffs. Separate actions agaist China, Mexico, Canada, India and Brazil. Currently
focus of legal challlenges.
Section 232 of the Trade Expansion
Act of 1962
US can impose tariffs or quotas as necessary to offset adverse impact
on national security
Commerce Dept. initiates investigation and makes recommendation to the President, who
makes the final decision. 3 investigations completed in 2018-19, 10 investigations in
progress. Usually take around 9 months.
Section 201 of the Trade Act of 1974
US can impose trade barriers if the US International Trade Commission
finds that an increase in imports is causing injury to the import-
competing US industry
US International Trade Commission must determine that there is an injury to a US industry
and makes recommendations, the President makes final decision and is not bound to
those recommendations. 2 investigations in 2017-18 into solar cells and washers.
Section 301 of the Trade Act of 1974
US can impose tariffs and quotas against foreign countries that deny
the US free trade agreements rights or engages in practices that are
unjustifiable, unreasonable ore discriminatory
US Trade Representative conducts investigation and makes preliminary recommendations,
the President makes final decision. Used to impose 4 sets of tariffs on China in 2018-19,
which are still in place.
Section 122 of the Trade Act of 1974
US can impose tariffs up to 15%, or quantitative restrictions, or both,
for up to 150 days against one or more countries with large balance of
payments surpluses
President can impose across the board without need for a prior investigation. Never used
before.
Section 338 of the Smoot-Hawley
Tariff Act of 1930
Authorizes the President to impose additional duties (up to 50%) for
five months on imports from countries that discriminate against US
commerce
President may act unilaterally upon finding discrimination against US goods; no formal
investigation required. Never used before.
